The liquid cooling teamâ€™s lab at Hack Week 2025

        
    

Liquid cooling has been around for years. What first sparked your interest in exploring it as a potential solution for Dropbox?
 Liquid cooling has been around for a while, and the industry has been actively experimenting with it. Weâ€™ve followed the technology closely, including by attending conventions like the Open Compute Project summit where itâ€™s a big topic. Bobby and I have seen these setups before and thought, this is really interestingâ€”how could we apply it to Dropbox? Weâ€™ve had that question in the back of our minds for years now, and now weâ€™re finally turning it into something concrete.
Bobby: Right. But itâ€™s not as simple as just plugging in a liquid-cooled server. We need the right infrastructure in place so that if future high-performance servers require it, weâ€™ll be ready. This project was about building that foundation.
So the challenge youâ€™re solving for is future-focusedâ€”preparing for next-gen hardware and higher power needs?
 Exactly. Itâ€™s about handling both individual server power draw and the overall data center footprint. As new servers demand more power, sticking with only air cooling would force us to spread them out over more space. With liquid cooling, we can stay efficientâ€”using less space, less energy, and potentially lowering costs.
How might this technology fit into our current and future infrastructure strategy, particularly with respect to our focus on supporting AI workloads?
 Weâ€™re seeing a greater need today for new solutions, especially with GPUs and AI workloads. These systems draw a huge amount of power and generate significant heat. While vendors arenâ€™t yet requiring liquid cooling for their top-tier GPUs, we know itâ€™s on the horizon. Air cooling may soon only support mid-range options.
Daniel: And with Dropbox focusing more on AI initiatives, it gave us the push we needed. As we expand into GPU-heavy systems, itâ€™s important to evaluate higher-powered setups. Hack Week was the perfect opportunity to explore that.


    
        
            
    

        

        
        
        

        
        
        

        
        

        
